```

You can do something like this in jQuery:

```
$('.link').click(function(){
    /*
        Let's get the slide number we want to goto
        by using what's in the "href" of the link that was clicked
        and we'll want to remove the hash.
    */
    var link = $(this).attr('href').replace('#','');
    /*
        So now the variable "link" will give us
        either 1, 2, 3 or whatever we put in the href.
    */
    /*
        Here's where the fake click happens.
        We'll find the li with the anchor that
        we want clicked using the selctor ":eq()",
        that selector is zero based so 0 = 1, so
        that's why I do (link - 1). Since we're putting
        a varible into a string we'll have to use a + operator
        to concatenate it all together.
    */
    $('#slides .pagination li:eq(' + (link - 1) + ') a').click();

    // this just prevents default click behavior
    return false;
});
```

So with that when you click say this link "<a href="#3" class="link">Slide 3</a>" jQuery will then click the pagination link 3 and then the slideshow will goto slide number 3.

