awasson:
I don't know if this is the appropriate spot to put this but I did find this reference while I was researching the problem of adding text pagination instead of numbers.

NOTE: The relies on adding a title attribute to each image in the slide set.

Rather than modifying the slidesjs source, I wrote a little block of jQuery that replaces the numbers in the pagination widget with the content of the title attributes for each image slide. In my example I used the current version (version 3) of the slidesjs code but it will work with any version with a little fine tuning.

Create the slideshow as usual and then loop through the images and update the pagination widget:

``` javascript

       $(function() {

      // Start slideshow
      $('#slides').slidesjs({
        width: 940,
        height: 528
      });

      // Update pagination widget with titles from slide images
      $('#slides img').each(function() {
        var slidetitle = $(this).attr('title');
        var index = $(this).attr('slidesjs-index');
        $('.slidesjs-pagination li a[data-slidesjs-item='+index+']').text(slidetitle);
      });

    });
```
. Hi o-l-e,

For your situation I'd modify the index variable.

The slide number is held in the slidesjs-index attribute. In the first example, the slidesjs-index is part of the image tag but when you add div's to the outside of each image it moves to the div so I changed the var index to get it's value from the parent div. 

``` javascript
var index = $(this).parent().attr('slidesjs-index');
```

I think moving forward with a permanent solution, the block of code will need to be more dynamic so that it finds the slidesjs-index attribute wherever it is in the branch. 
